  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 봉산(鳳山) : '
    value: 황해도 봉산. 그 이름에 의하여 명사(明使)가 정작 봉이 나타난 산으로 보아 성대(聖代)의 상서를 부(賦)로 노래했음.
  - key: '[주-D002] 기(蘷)와 용(龍) : '
    value: 순(舜)의 이름난 신하들이다.
  - key: '[주-D003] 이불을 가져가면서 잔소함이 : '
    value: 한유(韓愈)의 글에, “지금 벼슬하는 자들은 밤에 숙직하려고 이불을 가지고 들어가면서도 계집종을 돌아보며 잔소리를 쉬지 않는데, 은원외(殷員外)는 멀고 먼 회골(回鶻)에 사신으로 떠나면서도 늠름하게 간다.”는 말이 있다.
  - key: '[주-D004] 〈이 새가〉 …… 읊어졌고 : '
    value: 《시경》의 권아편(卷阿篇)은 서주(西周)의 덕을 칭송한 것인데, 그 중에, “봉황이 높은 메에서 울었다.”는 구절이 있다.
  - key: '[주-D005] 봉황이란 새는 : '
    value: 굴원의 〈이소(離騷)〉에, “봉황이 〈나쁜 새들에게〉속임을 받았다.”는 구절이 있다. 굴원과 송옥(宋玉)은 초나라 사람이므로, 그들의 작품인 사부(詞賦)를 초사(楚詞)라 한다.
  - key: '[주-D006] 무왕이 …… 상고할 수 있었네 : '
    value: 두 대는 하(夏)ㆍ은(殷)인데, 은나라 사람인 기자(箕子)가 하우(夏禹)의 홍범(洪範)을 전하였다는 말이다.
  - key: '[주-D007] 황극(皇極) : '
    value: 홍범(洪範)에 있는 말인데, “크게 중정(中正)한 도”라는 뜻이다.
  - key: '[주-D008] 봉각(鳳閣) : '
    value: 중서성(中書省)을 봉각(鳳閣)이라 하는데, 여기서는 명나라 사신 기순(祈順)을 일컬은 것이다.
  - key: '[주-D009] 사표(四表)가 …… 이르렀으며 : '
    value: 《서경》에 요(堯)의 덕(德)을 칭찬하는 말에, “빛이 사표(四表) 사방)에 입혀서 상하에 이른다[光被四表 格于上下].”는 구절이 있다.
  - key: '[주-D010] 십붕(十朋) : '
    value: 한 자 두 치의 큰 거북은 값이 십붕(十朋)이나 간다. 붕(朋)은 옛날 화폐(貨幣)의 수량이다.
  - key: '[주-D011] 박약(博約) : '
    value: 《논어》에, “문(文)으로써 박(博)하게 하고 예(禮)로써 약(約)하게 한다.”는 구절이 있다.
  - key: '[주-D012] 변화(卞和) : '
    value: 변화(卞和)가 형산(荊山)에서 박옥(璞玉)을 얻어서 초 문왕(楚文王)에게 바쳤는데, 박옥은 돌 속에 들어있는 옥이다. 문왕이 옥공(玉工)을 불러서 보였더니, 돌이요 옥이 아니라 하므로 변화에게 형벌을 주었더니 변화는 옥을 안고서 형산에서 울었다.
  - key: '[주-D013] 구포(九苞) : '
    value: 봉(鳳)은 구포(九苞)가 있는데, 포(苞)는 포함하였다는 뜻이다. 1은 입에는 명(命)을 포하였고, 2는 마음이 도(度)에 합하고, 5는 채색이 빛난다는 등의 아홉 가지가 있다 한다.
  - key: '[주-D001] 井 : '
    value: 幷
english:
  title: Rhapsody on Phoenix Mountain
  author: Kim Su-on
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I have heard it said that when a sage appears, a sage-king surely responds. Yet when a king receives heaven's mandate and governs, the transformative influence of benevolence knows no boundary between near and far. Thus auspicious signs may manifest in distant lands—the fire-eating fowl and the single-horned qilin offered to the Western lands bear witness to this. Though our nation occupies but one corner of the earth, we have been the first to receive the civilizing influence flowing eastward. Therefore, the phoenix's cry upon this mountain is no mere fable.

    Now that the imperial envoy, His Excellency of Phoenix Hall, has come in person to witness these events with his own eyes, he has composed a rhapsody and inscribed it upon stone cliffs, causing valleys to gleam with its radiance. Though I am but a rustic scholar, having examined the annals of our land and blended historical truth with refined expression, I humbly offer these verses in emulation of his elevated tone.

    For when extraordinary things occur in a nation, they await that nation's own voice to speak them—thus we prove the envoy's work speaks no falsehood, and return this as our great Ming's supreme blessing.

    The verses thus speak:

    There comes one of towering merit, a paragon of kingdoms—
    one who nurtures the spirit in lands of mist and mystery,
    soaring high above the nine horizons,
    inhaling the breath of the cosmos before its forming.
    With one drum-beat and one dance,
    heaven takes shape and earth finds balance.
    Qi transforms, phenomena shift,
    and nature's temperament opens and closes.

    We revere the illustrious Ming,
    whose fortune opens the millennium.
    Beyond mere excellence in governance and teaching,
    ritual, music, and culture bloom—
    the radiant palace spreads open as Yao and Shun's robes descend,
    and in the lofty halls, Qi and Long stand shoulder to shoulder.
    Where sovereign is sage and ministers worthy,
    virtue aligns and will unites,
    triumphant through a hundred ages,
    yet none surpass this present time.

    What fortune to have such noble scholars!
    They are the supreme auspices of human virtue.
    When poor and low, filial piety and fraternity flourish, customs rise.
    When elevated and high, the people's voice ascends and the ruler's grace spreads.

    Why should a flutter of ribbons shake the chariot wheels,
    making one rush back and forth, first and last?
    Now this great minister receives the warm words from above,
    adorned with the finest edicts.
    From our distant eastern realm to Yanshan's peaks—
    four thousand li in measure—
    he comes admiring Confucius's humble dwelling,
    carrying in his heart the vigor of ancient archery.
    Leaving at dawn, departing at dusk,
    yet no trembling heart, no fleeing form.
    With bow held high, those who follow shine brighter than distant travel,
    and bearing quilts while speaking gently is no foolishness.

    Observe our humble nation—
    mountains and rivers of surpassing beauty,
    whose equal is scarce in all the world.
    Famous peaks and mystic traces are beyond reckoning.

    Of old, when the Duke of Zhou honored the elderly and awakened Zhou's civilization,
    the phoenix cried upon high peaks, and the song of Kuan-a was born.
    When Qu Yuan wove his Li Sao,
    it became known as the Songs of Chu.

    The phoenix is a bird born only in times of sage-rule—
    it cannot be summoned by unvirtuous conduct,
    only by virtue is it fitting.
    It dwells in heaven, not in human hands,
    can be achieved through public good, never through private gain.

    When King Wu revolutionized against the Shang,
    Qi Zi refused to serve the Zhou court.
    Yet from him King Wu obtained the Grand Norm's nine categories,
    the transmitted wisdom of two dynasties.
    Thereupon the chariot was adorned as this bird's likeness,
    and music followed the Shao's harmony.
    He enfeoffed Qi Zi in Chosŏn to oversee the Eastern Marquis,
    and the Imperial Pole's governance spread its eight ordinances.

    Then the phoenix descended once,
    and people heard its harmonious song.
    Thus was a commandery established in that place,
    its name never fading.
    Even woodcutters and shepherds report glimpses
    of its plumage drifting on the wind.

    This bird drinks from the Yalu's waves,
    roosts in Kyerim's trees.
    When it comes, royal virtue governs well;
    when it departs, the state's governance falters.
    Not only do the elders speak of this—
    it is recorded in yellow scrolls.

    What fortune that Phoenix Hall's prince
    comes wandering to this distant eastern realm!
    Pitching his tent below that sacred peak,
    he contemplates its lingering echoes and sighs deeply.
    Composing his mighty verses to reveal their meaning,
    truly his words are without peer.
    He displays not merely this age's marvels,
    but makes manifest a thousand years' auspices.

    Thus shall the small nation's humble folk
    all look up to the celestial virtue's radiance,
    bathed in imperial grace,
    the borderlands dancing and leaping.
    Their entire beings suffused with warm influence,
    their ears filled with musical delight,
    converging on and returning to the Imperial Pole,
    drawn near to the Son of Heaven's sacred light.

    Yet consider the ancients' supreme governance—
    when light covered all four quarters,
    high and low resonated together,
    the hundred grains flourished in abundance,
    the seasons brought their timely signs.
    People practiced loyalty and faith,
    each household knew sufficiency.

    In such times, even when phoenixes called in the trees,
    they were seen as mere sparrows on hillsides.
    When divine dragons played in the pools,
    they were reckoned no different from common fish.
    Neither the great tortoise's ten-fold value
    nor the unicorn's single horn held esteem—
    for this was grounded in the Center's harmony,
    taught through learning both broad and refined.

    Ten thousand nations sent their tribute
    as the hundred rivers flow to the great sea;
    when one man found blessing,
    myriad stars circled the polar star.
    How much more when heaven's sphere shone luminous—
    why should we concern ourselves with lucky stars and auspicious clouds?

    Yet Kunshan's jade gleams in empty valleys,
    and Bian He wept before Chu's king.
    Emerald plumes and ivory arise in southern lands,
    and Liu Yan presented them to the imperial throne.
    Even humble plants possess the mettle
    to endure frost and defy snow—
    thus we choose the pine and bamboo.

    The phoenix, too, differs from common birds,
    the world esteems it rare.
    But is it better to seek it in antiquity
    than to find it in the present?
    Better to seek it in nature
    than to verify it in true virtue?

    This imperial minister takes the Six Arts and classical books as five colors,
    and makes moral teaching and ritual propriety its nine patterns.
    Risen through poetry, established through ritual,
    grounded in virtue, reliant on humanity—
    when these cause him to soar among officials,
    the empire calls it the morning-sun phoenix's cry.
    When these guide his governance of the four quarters,
    the people reverence his words.

    This is ancient though not ancient,
    phoenix though not phoenix—
    not through rarity of appearance does it overcome vulgar minds,
    but through harmony with all that is heard, it earns sage-wisdom's respect.

    Thus does he become the emblem of heaven's court,
    the very pattern of imperial ways,
    bringing forth the Ming's boundless rule of a million years.

    When the noble prince heard these words, his joy knew no bounds.
    Joy insufficient for mere silence, he sang:

    "If the phoenix's name
    can serve to signify supreme governance,
    then we mistake substance for shadow,
    abandoning the root to grasp the branch.
    Only when worthy men abound
    does the nation itself become the phoenix's song—
    not merely an auspice for this age,
    but a voice and substance echoing a thousand years hence."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Phoenix Mountain (Phongsan) was located in Hwanghae Province. The Ming envoy interpreted the mountain's name itself as evidence that an actual phoenix had appeared there, thus celebrating the auspices of the illustrious Ming age through this rhapsody.
  - key: ''
    value: Qi and Long (기와 용) were legendary ministers celebrated during the reign of Emperor Shun.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to bearing quilts while speaking gently alludes to Han Yu's account of official Yin Yuan-wai, who departed with dignity on distant mission rather than engaging in petty complaints.
  - key: ''
    value: 'The Kuan-a (권아) section of the Classic of Poetry celebrates Western Zhou virtue and contains the line: ''The phoenix cries upon the high peak.'''
  - key: ''
    value: According to Qu Yuan's Li Sao, the phoenix was deceived by inferior birds—a warning about virtue's vulnerability in corrupt times.
  - key: ''
    value: Qi Zi (기자), a wise minister of the Shang dynasty, transmitted to King Wu the Grand Norm (hongfan) containing the nine categories of statecraft, representing the wisdom of two dynasties.
  - key: ''
    value: The Imperial Pole (황극) refers to the doctrine of Supreme Rectitude found in the Grand Norm, representing the pinnacle of balanced governance.
  - key: ''
    value: Phoenix Hall (봉각) typically refers to the Central Secretariat; here it designates the Ming envoy.
  - key: ''
    value: The phrase about light covering the four quarters and resonating high and low echoes the Classic of Documents' description of Yao's virtue.
  - key: ''
    value: The great tortoise's ten-fold value (십붕) references the ancient practice of assessing rare items in units of currency.
  - key: ''
    value: 'The principle of learning ''both broad and refined'' (박약) comes from the Analects: achieving breadth through learning widely and refinement through ritual propriety.'
